Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.2

User

What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response

A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.

Example 1.3

User

What is a GAN?
AI Response

A Generative Adversarial Network pits a generator (creates fake data) against a discriminator (identifies
fakes), training each other until the generator produces realistic data.

Example 1.4

User

What is transfer learning?
AI Response

Transfer learning reuses a model trained on one task as a starting point for another related task, reducing
training time and data requirements significantly.

Example 1.5

User

What is precision vs recall?
AI Response

Precision is correct positive predictions / all positive predictions. Recall is correct positive predictions / all
actual positives. F1 score harmonically balances both.

Example 1.6

User

What is zero-shot learning?
AI Response

Zero-shot learning predicts unseen classes by leveraging semantic relationships or natural language task
descriptions, allowing LLMs to generalize without task-specific training.

Example 1.7

User

What is the vanishing gradient problem?
AI Response



In deep networks, gradients shrink exponentially during backpropagation, preventing early layers from
learning. Solutions include ReLU activations, residual connections, and LSTMs.

Example 1.8

User

What is backpropagation?
AI Response

Backpropagation computes gradients of the loss with respect to each weight by applying the chain rule
backwards through the network, enabling weight updates via gradient descent.

Example 1.9

User

What is machine learning?
AI Response

Machine learning is a branch of artificial intelligence that enables systems to learn and improve from
experience without being explicitly programmed.

Example 1.10

User

What is BERT?
AI Response

BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) is a pre-trained transformer model that
understands context from both directions in a sentence, excelling at NLP classification tasks.



